Theresa May's Stage
London — — The task before the newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May is formidable: to carry out the request of British voters — — or more precisely, voters from England and Wales — — to "leave the European Union" and to manage the far-reaching consequences of this action.
This challenge she faces surpasses that of all previous Prime Ministers in recent years.
But she may have the capability to complete this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has shown courage in a series of crises, May has all the tools needed to complete the task in her hands.
She is smart and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very good at taking control, and operates within self-defined boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues she deals with.
May has won in most of the battles she has been involved in, and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded tactics against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — — she needs to make full use of it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The Brexit process has already begun, and there is no doubt about that.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot go back.
She has repeatedly said "Brexit is Brexit", and her ministers also agree with her view.
But May has not yet given an exact definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare your food.
You would have a hard time knowing exactly what you are actually going to eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster Fry" — — eggs, bacon, pork sausage, black pudding, potato, soda bread, and fried tomato — — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
You may feel very differently about various possible combinations depending on your environment and personal preferences.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people may focus mainly on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others may be more concerned about gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win hearts or punish Britain for leaving the EU (sometimes such inflammatory rhetoric is prevalent, such as what the newly appointed British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson called "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we British often forget that everyone — — including the EU and all its member states — — has their own political or commercial interests they vow to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine what Britain's goals should be after the difficult negotiations on the UK's relationship with the EU (and in the trade field, its relationship with the world) begin, based on reality?
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six separate topics that need to be negotiated), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter, who is 11 years old now, may already be starting university!
) We must clarify the priorities in order to prevent the negotiations from taking even longer.
The goal is certainly to achieve a balance between British exports and services (especially financial services) entering other European countries and restricting the movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they will need to make in other areas.
May needs to make full use of her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the rationality of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will find that dissatisfaction is not only from a particular part — — which is inevitable — — but from all.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing social divide in Britain exposed by Brexit.
Blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have long been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called proxy — — the EU — — of globalization.
English metropolises — — especially London — — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have gained nothing.
Many members of the working-class have become victims of populist promises of the Brexit campaign due to lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by the leftist leader Jeremy Corbyn.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will drive out immigrants who suppress wages and redirect hundreds of millions of pounds that were previously given to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would bring back a safer and more prosperous past for the UK.
Those who supported Brexit cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can it cut off immigration from the EU.
Any such measures would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturn leads to a decline in immigration, those who voted for Brexit may still feel disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public services remain under pressure.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already sparked an uncontrollable storm of populist sentiment.
Just as Donald Trump was powerless to improve the situation of working-class voters in the United States, the UK's Brexit cannot possibly bring benefits to those who chose it, no matter how it seems.
Although it has many advantages, such a challenge may still be beyond May's ability to overcome.
